				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$k(m)={k}_{\max }\left(\frac{d(m)}{{d}_{\max }}\right)$$\end{document}k(m)=kmaxd(m)dmaxfor each concentration number m of dosage d, where \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${d}_{\max }$$\end{document}dmax represents the maximum dosage value. Hence, the forward problem will use a different death rate for each different drug concentration, while the growth rate will not depend on drug concentration.
